5. Feature Groups
The feature layer will be divided into five groups.
Trend
•	rolling returns
•	moving-average gaps
•	above/below trend flags
Stress
•	drawdown
•	realized volatility
•	downside volatility
•	deterioration speed
Confirmation
•	HY / IG agreement
•	JNK confirmation
•	breadth across primary proxies
Divergence
•	credit versus SPY relative behavior
•	credit weakness while equities remain firm
•	credit weakness plus rising VIX
Persistence
•	rolling score average
•	recent score sign consistency
•	regime durability
________________________________________
6. Score Architecture
The model will compute five required sub-scores:
•	credit_trend_score
•	credit_stress_score
•	credit_confirmation_score
•	credit_divergence_score
•	credit_persistence_score
These will be combined into:
•	credit_regime_score
Recommended baseline weights:
•	trend = 0.35
•	stress = 0.25
•	confirmation = 0.20
•	divergence = 0.10
•	persistence = 0.10
Final score range:
•	-1.00 = strongest Risk-Off
•	0.00 = neutral
•	+1.00 = strongest Risk-On
________________________________________
7. Regime Rules
Discrete regime labels will be assigned from the continuous score.
•	score >= +0.35 → Risk-On
•	-0.35 < score < +0.35 → Neutral
•	score <= -0.35 → Risk-Off
These thresholds must remain configurable.
________________________________________
8. Transition Flags
The model will support these flags:
•	flag_early_warning
•	flag_stress_acceleration
•	flag_recovery
•	flag_confirmed_risk_on
These flags are intended to describe transitions, not replace the primary regime label.
________________________________________
9. Expected Outputs
The model must return:
A. Daily DataFrame
•	raw input series
•	proxy ratios
•	engineered features
•	sub-scores
•	final score
•	discrete label
•	flags
•	diagnostics
B. Latest snapshot dictionary
•	latest date
•	latest score
•	latest label
•	sub-score values
•	confirmation state
•	divergence state
•	VIX state
•	flags
•	top drivers
•	plain-language explanation
________________________________________
10. Robustness Requirements
The implementation must:
•	validate required columns
•	sort and align dates
•	handle missing values cleanly
•	guard against division by zero
•	preserve NaN where history is insufficient
•	use stable deterministic column names
•	keep all thresholds centralized in config
•	avoid hidden state and side effects
________________________________________
11. Intended Integrations
The model is designed to plug into:
•	macro dashboard
•	sector rotation overlay
•	risk-on / risk-off engine
•	tactical allocation model
•	trade risk filter
•	broader multi-model research stack
________________________________________
12. Limitations
This model is useful but not pure credit spread measurement because ETF proxies contain:
•	duration effects
•	carry effects
•	liquidity effects
•	ETF structure effects
VIX is also supportive, not primary. It confirms stress but should not dominate the regime engine.
